What kind of conclusion can be made based on these figures?¶

There are two peak points shown in the 1st, 4th figures which indicate Malaysia faced second-waves of the covid-19 attack. Based on my observation in the 1st, 4th figures we can see that when the new covid-cases are reported, most likely the victims are affected by the covid-19 virus. Fortunately, based on the 3rd figure the victims are also fast at recovery so there are not many death cases are reported. Regarding the 2nd figure, the highest reported cases are around 70 till 80 on that particular day, not many foreign cases are brought into Malaysia since the citizens cannot go overseas for traveling because of the policy.¶


Story-Telling¶

At the beginning of the year, we have the lowest covid-19 cases reported in Malaysia, mainly is because the situation is still under control said by the government since they implemented a lot of policies to prevent the citizens from going out of the house frequently. Common policies such as citizens must stay within 10KM in their area, one driver is only allowed in one car, they will be fined if they are not wearing the face-mask, etc. The second scenario might be the virus is not mutated yet or perhaps, some of the citizens already vaccinated, which explained the cases remained bottom from January 2021 till October 2021.¶

Starting in October 2020, the covid-19 case started to increase rapidly mainly is caused by new covid-19 species and it has been brought into Malaysia. Example of Corona Mutated species are Alpha, Beta, Delta, and omicron. The situation starting to turn into chaos in Malaysia because they faced insufficient test kits, vaccines, lack of equipment in the hospital to take care of the patients, the citizen is less care about the discipline or lack of self-control, lack of proper prevention plans, etc. Hence, these are the factors that caused the cases to grow rapidly in Malaysia.¶

# Calculate the infection and recovery rate in Malaysia
# then visualize it

newCase = fCTotal['cases_new']/100
recoveredCase = fCTotal['cases_recovered']/100
In [94]:
# Check the recovered and new cases

# figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(12,4), facecolor='#293952')
ax.set_facecolor('#293952')

# Plot the lines
plt.plot(fCTotal.date, newCase, color='#FDAC53')
plt.plot(fCTotal.date, recoveredCase, color='#55A380')

# Set the name/title
plt.title('Infection and Recovery Rate Comparison\n', loc='left', color='w', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Date', color='w')
plt.ylabel('Number of the cases(%)', color='w')

ax.tick_params(axis='both', colors='white')
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_color('w')
ax.spines['bottom'].set_color('w')

# Set the grid
ax.set_axisbelow(True)
ax.yaxis.grid(color='#FDAC53', linestyle='dashed', alpha=0.5)

# Set the legend
legend = plt.legend(['Infection', 'Recovered'], frameon=False, ncol=2)
plt.setp(legend.get_texts(), color='w')

Although Malaysia has a high infection rate the victims are still able to recover themself quickly, which proofed that the recovery rate is high as well. This should be seen as a positive development or a piece of good news, not only for Malaysia but for the whole world. After changing the Cabinets, the current government started to control back the situation which both rates drop drastically at the end of 2021, thank our new health minister's contribution.¶
